<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN214">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ceykuvaṅ kollō nalviṉai yeṉavē</l>
<l>yaiya maṟāar kacaṭīṇṭu kāṭci</l>
<l>nīṅkā neñcattut tuṇivil lōrē</l>
<l>yāṉai vēṭṭuva ṉāṉaiyum peṟumē</l>
<l>kuṟumpūḻ vēṭṭuvaṉ vaṟuṅkaiyum varumē</l>
<l>yataṉā, luyarnta vēṭṭat tuyarntici ṉōrkkuc</l>
<l>ceyviṉai maruṅki ṉeyta luṇṭeṉiṟ</l>
<l>ṟoyyā vulakattu nukarcciyuṅ kūṭun</l>
<l>toyyā vulakattu nukarcci yilleṉiṉ</l>
<l>māṟip piṟappi ṉiṉmaiyuṅ kūṭu</l>
<l>māṟip piṟavā rāyiṉu mimayattuk</l>
<l>kōṭuyarn taṉṉa tammicai naṭṭut</l>
<l>tītil yākkaiyoṭu māytaṟavat talaiyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>For those who have not cut off the doubt (2ab)</l>
<l>as to whether they would do good work/deeds, (1) </l>
<l>in hearts from which a flaw-gathering sight has not departed (2cd-3ab)</l>
<l>  they are without determination. (3cd)</l>
<l>An elephant hunter will get elephant, (4)</l>
<l>and a quail hunter will come [back] empty-handed. (5)</l>
<l>Therefore, if there is attaining [their] higher desires</l>
<l>on account of the deeds done for those who are high, (6f.)</l>
<l>enjoyment is met in the imperishable world, (8)</l>
<l>and if there is no enjoyment in the imperishable world, (9)</l>
<l>the absence of birth after changing is met. (10)</l>
<l>If one is not born [again] after changing, (11a-c)</l>
<l>the very best is being gone along with a flawless body (13)</l>
<l>after erecting one’s fame as high as the peak of the Himālaya. (11d-12)   </l>
</lg>
    </div>
